Inflation in Europe has derailed on food
Accelerated inflation, as measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, according to the European Community's Statistics Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only indicated 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the policy interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, with higher commodity prices and lower unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, this is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject at a later stage.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent has been a record in the last twelve years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area took off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market ratings have increased by 88 per cent and soybean prices have also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 per cent, and last month a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly in early December. Thus, since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never seen so little socialist support before, i.e. 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one-fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent throughout the population.
Of the faithful voters some went to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been higher, it amounts to 41 per cent and, according to 46 per cent, the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population is planning to worsen and only one-tenth is planning to improve the situation.
Last December, 71 per cent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in Gallup's previous polls, found that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 per cent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 per cent trust the President of Fidesz.
One indicator of political change is the proportion of society thinking that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be addressed without a change of government.
While after the riots last October, 35 per cent of those polled wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, at present this rate represents only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believes that the holding of new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 per cent of respondents replied that they would certainly vote and the additional 20 per cent said that they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 per cent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent would probably participate. According to the current intentions, the result of the referendum would be no doubt.
74 per cent of people would say no to higher education fees, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 per cent would say no to hospital expenses.
When we look at only the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital expenses.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the commercial triangle of Budaörs maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, the difference being that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a value increase well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already soared" in department food stores last December, have no longer risen sharply compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded by 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but the prices of turkey fillet, nuts and poppy rose sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to only 139 forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the recorded bottle of two liters of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it only cost 257 forints the recorded bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive shopping cart with this year's cheapest shopping cart, we see a gap of 12 percent while the difference between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, although the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already evident in last year's Christmas prices.
This process perplexed trade, so hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a big profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the prices of the Daily Basket has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and prices at the least priced increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By bringing the two Christmas seasons closer, we have seen a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some essential supplies, the Institute of Statistics has seen a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the daily basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 per cent compared to the base.
According to the evidence, flour suppliers hold a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the brutal price increase also accepted by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-storage food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important tails formed at the crates of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less significant in the provinces, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the Chief Medical Officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save money on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected on a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient has been isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident came out of the hospital but shortly after he had to return there due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to perform an important operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections from a multidrug-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Medical Officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e., by methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant bacterium that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged functioning of the immune system, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicaemia, on elderly patients, with small weights or with a weakened organism.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily lives of hospitals.
Above all, we must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only there or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the health care staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they have MRSA, however infection cannot always be prevented.
The sampling of the sample is not in mode
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favourable to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-drug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and seniors' residences, hospitals should control inpatients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases occur only if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the Chief Medical Officer of the Epidemiological Centre.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian directives for the recovery of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but this is not always taken into account by hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, there are significant gaps in hospitals too in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemics, patients should be separated from each other by at least 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, save on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are complied with, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable way or the spread of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why this infection is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified as its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-drug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, who was the author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness.
The official statement concerning the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement was drawn up.
It may be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has resigned from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led to a state of drunkenness or stunned, communicated Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former chief of the 22nd district police station crushed a 55-year-old man who stood in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, in the Kossuth Lajos street of the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(In fact, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code, a car that starts a turn must let the pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being taken to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and asked for his retirement because, according to police communication, this accident greatly upset him.
The investigation of this case is carried out by the Public Prosecutor's Office in Budapest.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the outset with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
Additional EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday with a total value of EUR 400 million for a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The agreement on the appropriation of EUR 150 million also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, the remaining EUR 150 million will be available for use later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a €50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope primarily as part of the research and development project to be carried out at Debrecen University.
During the negotiations, the Metro Line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible amendment of the original contract once Hungary has finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the EURIBOR-related interest rate, with a grace period of 8 years and no commitment fee.
Bulgaria, the paradise of the EU real estate market
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this Balkan country little mentioned in the past.
What, or who is buying from this EU market that is still the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and houses by the cheap sea.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nessebar but they are more and more searching for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik region as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, commercial and office areas promise the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time looking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others arrive from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the shores of the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed as one of the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- or long-term capital gains.
The price of the capital's buildings is constantly rising as a result of increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices is essentially greater than the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of professionals end on Tuesday, but Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Road Map to define the efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol emission reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there are strong discussions on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss exact figures, although it was prepared to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 per cent from 1990 levels by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, without emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The Kyoto Protocol aid fund will be managed by a 16-member Board of Directors, probably under the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), reported Piac es Profit (Market and Profit).
Six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor confirms the EU's ambition to retain its flagship role in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 from the level reached in 1990, regardless of the success of the signing of the "Post-2012 Agreement", and was prepared to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the Kyoto Protocol countries had achieved a total reduction of 5.2 per cent, and all 15 EU members of that time made a commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the 1985-1987 period, our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, commitments to reduce below the Kyoto Protocol values would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was stressed in the new IPCC report, an international scientific body, which won the UN Nobel Peace Prize for climate change.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the Earth's average temperature by more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which scientists believe would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British Army units report on the video-sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has been passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan are uploading video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken with miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are monitored at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to Londres or the compatriots load them on the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 footage online through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as the Defenceheadquarters in the spring of 2007 and released videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Department (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were posted online to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to publicize to the general public the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
Propaganda published through this channel costs virtually nothing compared to the usual advertising of recruitment on television, communicated to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the soundness of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game
The army is bothered because, apart from the carefully censored and composed videos, amateur videos have passed through the sharing site that also present, for example, the deaths of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been uploaded showing the areas of operation in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been speeding up the loading of these videos.
Americans recruit a little differently using the free downloadable America's Army Shooting Game. In this game the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
