The forces of the mega strike gather
The League's trade unions and the National Association of Workers' Councils will set up their strike commission on Friday to coordinate Monday's indefinite strike.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the Health Insurance Act, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic congestion as rail traffic will be stopped almost completely and employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1 p.m.
On Friday afternoon, the league's trade unions will make known the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The strike commission of LIGA - MOSZ will also be set up, it will serve as coordinator of the actions of Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and, from Monday, the organizations joining the strike will stop work for an indefinite period if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the law on health funds, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the Health Insurance Act, the trade unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike action.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on what further action to take.
According to the National Assembly's Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the Health Insurance Act will take place only late in the evening or even at night.
As a result of the strike scheduled for Monday, important traffic stoppages are planned: the railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning part of public transport in Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the track will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call for strike action, the list of which is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations report an indefinite strike, while others reported a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railway) and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ) failed to reach agreement on the minimum services, but, as the Christmas holidays approached, more and more people were taking the train.
According to current communications, public transport in Budapest will strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., Budapest Airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the Industrial Unions of Electricity and Thermal Energy of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Union of Teachers have called to strike for 2 hours and 2 hours to 8 hours respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country alternating, the Union of Health and Social Workers (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal for health reform and to submit a new concept to social debate.
The second claim requires that the new retirement calculation method to be introduced from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim seeks a guarantee, in respect of retirement before the legal age, that would allow the functions that deserve it to be transferred to the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), attached to the Unions of the League, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning the secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased country risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital (Risk Analysis Division), the activity of the Hungarian Guard, set up last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary) increases, in several aspects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning", the society reports that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur as a result of the worsening ethnic tension already existing between the gypsy and non-gypsy population of Hungary".
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy, which is likely to cause this situation, is the main reason for this.
As they say, this is due to one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: "public actors passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings which based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians".
The problem is compounded, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are reinforced and the advent of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, due to the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular regarding confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country".
They recall that, following a greater publicity given to the reorganization of radical and extreme right Hungarian groups since autumn 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 calling themselves the "national self-defence association".
"The common feature of these rallies is that they define themselves as a civilian organization as they publicly declare the preparation of their adherents to defence missions (catastrophes, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, moreover, by mentioning the incapacity of the police, of the army, in other words of the state," they added.
They pointed out that everything was going according to the method which, based on the resentment of the political society and the parties, sought to disguise different political ambitions from a civil point of view.
The emphasis on civility and association status therefore serves only to avoid the legal traps of registering such associations in court, but they are also a political strategy.
