The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganise the working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
Holidays are not uniform in the EU and in the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holidays and days of rest.
Rest days are often linked to religious festivals or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the New Year's Evers can rest quietly.
Moreover, in a year, we have a total of eleven parties marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, in commemoration of the revolution of 1848, as is October 23 which is also the memorial day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, on May 1 is Labor Day, and on November 1 and 2, we remember the members of our family and friends who died.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, depending on the calendar, it has become common to reorganize working days in cases where there is only one working day before or after the party marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for extended weekends by working or going to school the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a special regulation on replacement days for days preceding or following holidays.
The Act extends to all employers and their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, institutions that rotate continuously and in service, by reason of their vocation, and also to days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24th, life ends almost all over the country because according to experiences the majority of people do more overtime or take vacations they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many parties fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized the first time around the Labour Day to allow employees to stay at home four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25, will be a day of work to have a day of rest on Friday, May 2.
Another change is scheduled for October 23rd: Saturday, October 18th will be a working day replacing Friday, 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year will be marked by the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
