The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and deportation, his lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of leaving students between the ages of 6 and 7 to give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear while any representation of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was punishable by lashes.
This 54-year-old British teacher at the Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested on Sunday at her home and charged with violating Islam and sedition, under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints from parents of students to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually goes back to September, when this teacher asks her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the class's teddy bear.
"Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed," says school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with a picture of the bear followed by the legend "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself did not carry any label with this name, but the problem is simply the representation of the prophet as an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name", he says it is only an "innocent mistake".
Opinion shared by many of the teacher's students who describe her as "very attentive to her students" and "who never talks about religion in the classroom".
