Spectacular repair on space station
It took more than seven hours of space work for astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates from the International Space Station (ISS) to perform the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel, indispensable for the continuation of the station's scientific activities.
A risky release that has accumulated the records because of its duration, its remoteness from the habitable modules, the speed with which it was imagined, tools "bricoled" by astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem appeared on Tuesday as astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the space shuttle, a large cylindrical room to soon host the European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see box).
This module is a kind of dock for laboratory modules.
But we need to be able to supply them with electricity.
The crew's second task was therefore to move a solar panel power generation module weighing 17.5 tonnes, already present on the ISS, to put it in its final position.
After moving it, the crew began the redeployment of the solar panels from the module, which have a wingspan of 76 metres.
And that's where one of the panels, which unfold like accordions, was damaged about a meter by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment was stopped so as not to further damage the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally required to perform a control exit from the Discovery Shuttle and then go and repair another solar panel whose rotation system was defective, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to caracole at the end of the 30 meters of length of the remote control arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to perform the repair.
It is one of the best "spacewalker" in the Nasa.
Large, resistant, very skillful, it has a very developed torso and long arms.
At 46 years of age, this training physician was therefore tasked with "operating" the "injured" solar panel.
After precisely inspecting the damage, he severed the faulty cable and installed some kind of "claps" on the damaged area.
He was assisted by a second "spacewalker" remaining near the airlock and, from the inside, by other astronauts including Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a hockey mini-cane wrapped in insulation to avoid electrocution on solar panels producing several hundred volts, was designed and "briccoled" by astronauts aboard the station.
After the operation was completed, Scott Parazynski waited for the panel to be fully deployed before making an inventory of his tools and returning to the inside of the station.
Yesterday afternoon, astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery for a return to Earth scheduled for Wednesday.
