A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in open access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen, Hesse, were so far only searchable for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his successors in title.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including France, Germany, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be carried out "in particular on the movement of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the public opening of these nominative documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The registers of the concentration camps or arrest warrants drawn up by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, possibly, to prove their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are processing tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
