The harmonised consumer price index rose by five-tenths in November, up to 4.1%.
This indicator, which is then used by Eurostat to incorporate it into the calculation of the rate of inflation in the European Union, provides a balance sheet on price developments in Spain during the month of November.
Its publication is in line with the policy of Eurostat and the European Central Bank (ECB) by providing data comparable in time and quality to those produced in the United States.
The leading indicator is calculated using the same process used for the Harmonized Consumer Price Index, but using various statistical modelling methods to estimate the information that is not yet available for publication.
