It's not Warhols' crates.
The one who connects the Swedish concepts with the wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety "Stockholm Type" Brillo-Boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the internal research of the Stockholm Moderna Museet now leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the Pontus Hulten Museum donated in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as much of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Stockholm Type", which circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting sequence of artistic and curatoric productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York its first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the powder soap cartons "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo carton cases: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered by right into the history of art and auction, as Andy Warhol's original Brillo-Boxes authorized, with the name "Stockholm Type".
Some of them have reached over $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum mistakenly claimed that later about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have ceded to him.
Indeed, Hultén's 105 cases were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St Petersburg.
By that time Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three more of Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The texture of the copies that date back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was applied directly without a background layer on the laminated panels, using a paint roller - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These crates were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official list of Brillo-Boxes," suggests Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July the Authentication Board of course announced that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then, we've had an inexorable silence.
Manila Rebel Soldiers Abandon
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers abandon, the same who had cut themselves off in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the President of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters in the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The soldiers loyal to power had shortly before stormed the hotel using tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had cut themselves off for hours in the building.
About half of them were held in court on Wednesday due to a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse himself with about 30 sympathizers.
Military police officers, who normally had to watch them, had apparently deserted in his favor and had joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The troops loyal to the government closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have had enough," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us".
General Danilo Lim, who commanded before the Scout Ranger elite unit, said other army units soon wanted to join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a major protest against the President on Wednesday.
His government had been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
Since 2003, Manila's finance district has been the scene of the attempted mutiny of some 200 members of the army against Arroyo.
The insurgency broke almost 24 hours after the army refused to join it.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
